so this is only tangentially related, buuuuuutttt, the reason you cant take photographs of the constitution (or any really old document) is because any really bright light, like the flash function on cameras, will gradually fade the inks color.  the National Archives used to allow photography without flash, but so many people used flash anyways (accidentally or not) that the document was starting to degrade.  so they had to ban it outright to prevent further damage, so that people in the future could come and see exactly what was written all those hundreds of years ago.  

source: I'm in library school and I got to go on a tour there with one of the archivists and that's what they told me.
